article.description:
Glen Davis had 24 points and 11 rebounds to
lead No. 25 LSU to a 65-61 victory over stingy Auburn on Saturday.
article.headline: Davis' double-double keeps No. 25 LSU rolling
article.linkText: Davis' double-double keeps No. 25 LSU rolling
article.story: AUBURN, Ala. (AP) -- The LSU Tigers aren't exactly winning pretty these days. They certainly look good in first place, though. Glen Davis had 24 points and 11 rebounds to lead No. 25 LSU to a 65-61 victory over stingy Auburn on Saturday. Tasmin Mitchell scored his only two points of the game with 30 seconds left, breaking a 61-61 tie. Darrell Mitchell added two free throws down the stretch to give LSU (18-7, 10-2 Southeastern Conference) its third straight win and fourth in five games. The Tigers are two games ahead of Alabama in the SEC West, with winnable games remaining at Vanderbilt and South Carolina and home against Kentucky and Ole Miss. Their latest victory certainly didn't come easy. Auburn (10-13, 2-10) had a couple of chances to tie or take the lead after Tasmin Mitchell's big shot, but Quantez Robertson missed a 3-pointer with 7 seconds left and Ronny LeMelle missed a jumper three seconds later. Davis corralled the rebound off LeMelle's miss with four seconds left, and LSU didn't clinch the victory until Darrell Mitchell scored sank two free throws with 1 second left. Darrell Mitchell finished with 16 points. Tasmin Mitchell was 1-for-3 from the field while battling foul trouble, and a sore back, for most of the night. "It was really aching," Mitchell said. "The last basket didn't really make the pain go away, but I'm happy that I came through for my team when they really needed it." Tyrus Thomas added 14 points and eight rebounds for LSU. LeMelle led Auburn with 21 points, 16 of which came in the first half. Josh Dollard had with 12 points and Robertson added 10. Auburn has now lost all four of its meetings against ranked opponents, including an 84-69 defeat at LSU earlier this month. Auburn has also lost three in a row and five of its last six. "The guys are hurt and frustrated. We just can't get it done," Auburn head coach Jeff Lebo said. "We had chances up until the end. The disappointment level is up there."
